<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01046c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01046c">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01046c"> 46(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Odyss = 12 predom passions <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n01046c"><li>FW 76.02f </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n01046c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n01046c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n01046c">MS BL 47472-156</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:031 <a name="d1A3d" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#d1A3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/d1A3d.htm#n01046c">Draft: I.4&sect;1A.3</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The twelve predominant passions possibly refer to the six concupiscible and six irascible passions identified in the scholastic tradition. In III q.3540, Thomas Aquinas discusses these six basic passions of the concupiscible: love and hate; desire and aversion; pleasure and pain; and six basic passions of the irascible: hope and despair; fear and daring (or boldness); anger divided into anger directed towards good ends (ie, righteous anger) and anger directed towards evil or corrupt ends. </mm> </dd></dl>
